Thus, the fixed code:

```java
public Object set(int index, Object object) {
    int pos = indexOf(object);
    Object removed = super.set(index, object);

    if (pos == -1) {
        // new object not in list, so update set
        set.remove(removed);
        set.add(object);
    } else if (pos == index) {
        // setting to same element, nothing to do
        // (the set already contains object)
    } else {
        // object already exists at pos, we need to remove the duplicate at pos
        super.remove(pos);
        set.remove(removed);
        // object is already in set, no need to add
    }

    return removed;
}
```

But we can simplify: we always want to remove `removed` from set and add `object` to set, except when we are removing the duplicate at another position (in which case we also need to remove that duplicate from list). Actually, we can do:

- After super.set, remove `removed` from set.
- If `object` is not already in the set (pos == -1), add it to set.
- If pos != -1 and pos != index, also remove the duplicate at pos.

That is equivalent. But we must be careful not to do set.add(object) when object is already present, because that would be a no-op.

So minimal fix: add handling for pos == -1.

